                        <p> <hi rend="initialcap">C</hi>ASE 3.&#8212;<name type="person">Private Cyrus G. Chatterton</name>, <name type="organization">Co. C, 24th N.
                                Y. Cav.</name>; age 17; was admitted <date type="admit" when="1864-07-24">July 24, 1864</date>, scorbutic and
                                much emaciated from long-continued diarrh&#339;a.  On <date type="injury" when="1864-08-03">August 3</date>
                                        the patient experienced difficulty in opening his mouth and
                                        complained of sore throat. The fauces were found inflamed
                                        and the tonsils covered with matter. Iron and stimulants
                                        were administered, with chlorate of potash as a gargle and
                                        counter-irritation externally.  On the 5th mucous r&#226;les were
                                        heard over the chest. An emetic was given but without
                                        effect.  He died asphyxiated on <date type="death" when="1864-08-06">the 6th</date>.  "The constitution of
                                        the patient being scorbutic and his condition very low there
                                        was not a chance for tracheotomy."&#8212;<hi rend="italic"><name type="hospital" key="214">Fairfax Seminary Hospital</name>, Va.</hi> </p>                        
